The reason for using a different "flavor" of tap-hold for R versus Space comes down to the frequency and nature of how we type those specific keys at 60 wpm.

In Kanata, tap-hold-press (what you use for Space) and tap-hold-release (what I suggested for R) handle the "decision" of whether you meant to tap or hold differently.

1. Space: The "Press" Logic (tap-hold-press)
You use tap-hold-press for your Space/Nav key.

How it works: If you press Space and then press any other key, Kanata immediately decides you are holding Space for the Nav layer.

Why it's good for Space: Space is a "thumb" key. In normal typing, you almost never press Space at the exact same time as another key (you usually tap space between words). Because of this separation, you want the Nav layer to be "snappy" and activate the moment your next finger hits a key.

2. R: The "Release" Logic (tap-hold-release)
I suggested tap-hold-release for your R/Symbol key.

How it works: The Symbol layer only activates if you press R, press J, and then release the R key while J is still down (or after). If you just tap R and J quickly in sequence (rolling your fingers), it will still output "rj" instead of "[".

Why it's vital for R: Unlike Space, R is in the middle of your typing "rolls." At 60 wpm, you often have "key overlap"—you might start pressing the next letter before you've fully let go of the r.

If we used tap-hold-press on R, and you typed the word "red" quickly, Kanata might see the overlap between r and e and think, "Oh, he's holding R to use a layer!" and you'd end up with a symbol or a dead key instead of the letter e.

Summary Comparison
Feature	tap-hold-press (Space)	tap-hold-release (R)
Trigger	Activates layer as soon as next key is pressed.	Activates layer only if held and released after next key.
Pros	Feels instantaneous and responsive.	Much harder to trigger by accident during fast typing.
Cons	High risk of "accidental layers" during fast rolls.	Slightly more deliberate; requires a "clean" hold.
By using tap-hold-release for R, you protect your typing speed. You won't have to slow down or worry about "r" turning into a modifier just because you're typing words like "rain," "road," or "tree" quickly.

